<div id="header">
<h1><img src="../images/icons/CourseInfo-yellow_64.png" />&nbsp;Resources</h1>
</div>
<div sizset="0" sizcache="1" id="body">
<p> These resources may be of use to you: </p>
<ul>
  <li><em>Java</em>
    <ul>
      <li>The Java environment provides the virtual machine that BlueJ runs in. You can get	it at<!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/Java download page.lbi" -->
Oracle's Java <a href="http://java.sun.com/javase/downloads/index.html" target="_blank">download page</a><!-- #EndLibraryItem -->. You should download <!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/JDK description.lbi" -->

the latest <em>non-beta</em> version of the Java 2 Standard Edition (J2SE).  You need the JDK, but you do not need NetBeans or the Enterprise Edition.
<!-- #EndLibraryItem --></li>
      <li>The <a href="http://www.bluej.org" target="_blank">BlueJ</a> Java development environment.</li>
      <li>The Java   7 API <a href="http://java.sun.com/javase/7/docs/api/" target="_blank">documentation</a>.</li>
      <li>The <a href="http://java.sun.com/docs/books/tutorial/" target="_blank">Java Tutorials</a>.</li>
      <li>Bruce Eckel&rsquo;s <a href="http://www.mindview.net/Books/TIJ" target="_blank">Thinking in Java, 3rd Edition</a> is a <em>free</em> online Java textbook</li>
      <li><a href="../../files/pccdoc/index.html" target="_blank">documentation</a> generated by <a href="http://java.sun.com/j2se/javadoc/index.jsp" target="_blank">javadoc</a> for the stdin package written by PCC instructor <a href="http://spot.pcc.edu/~mtrigobo" target="_blank">Michael Trigoboff</a> that implements command line input. You can download this package as <a href="../../files/pcc.jar">pcc.jar</a>. (<!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/pcc.jar download.lbi" -->
If Internet Explorer insists on downloading this file as pcc.zip, just rename the file to pcc.jar.<!-- #EndLibraryItem -->) You can also download the <a href="../../files/pccdoc.zip">documentation</a> as a .zip file. </li>
      <li>If you want to read an industrial strength introduction to Java, I recommend <a href="http://java.sun.com/docs/books/javaprog/" target="_blank">The Java Programming Language</a>,  		written by some of the people who originally created Java.</li>
      <li>Java byte codes are described in <a href="http://java.sun.com/docs/books/vmspec/index.html" target="_blank">The Java Virtual Machine Specification</a>.  		Click on the &ldquo;View HTML&rdquo; link to view the book online.</li>
      <li>A book that may be of use in learning to use Eclipse: <a href="http://www.aw-bc.com/catalog/academic/product/0,1144,0321305027,00.html" target="_blank"> The Java Developer's Guide to Eclipse</a>. </li>
      <li>It is important to test your code systematically. In Java, you can do that using <a href="http://junit.sourceforge.net/" target="_blank">JUnit</a>. Here are tutorials about how to use JUnit <a href="http://code.google.com/p/t2framework/wiki/JUnitQuickTutorial" target="_blank">in a command-line environment</a>, and how to use it <a href="http://www.cs.uu.nl/wiki/pub/WP/TrainingInSoftwareTesting/JUnit_with_Eclipse.pdf" target="_blank">in Eclipse</a>.</li>
      <li>The <a href="http://www.pjug.org" target="_blank">Portland Java User's Group (PJUG)</a> is a local group for  		those interested in Java.</li>
      </ul>
  </li>
  <li><em>C++
    </em>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="http://www.oreilly.com/catalog/core/" target="_blank">C++ The Core Language</a>, by Gegory Satir and Doug Brown. This is an excellent introduction to C++ if you already know C. </li>
      <li> Bruce Eckel has a free online C++ textbook called <a href="http://www.mindview.net/Books/TICPP/ThinkingInCPP2e.html" target="_blank">Thinking in C++, 2nd Edition</a>. </li>
      <li>For some of the more advanced features and concepts of C++, the following books will be helpful:
        <ul>
          <li><a href="http://www.awprofessional.com/title/0201309831" target="_blank">C++ FAQs, 2nd Edition</a>, by Marshall Cline, Greg Lomow, and Mike Girou.</li>
          <li><a href="http://www.awprofessional.com/title/0321334876" target="_blank">Effective C++, 3rd Edition</a> and <a href="http://www.awprofessional.com/title/020163371X" target="_blank">More Effective C++</a> by Scott Meyers.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>For the C++ Standard Library, these books and web sites will be helpful:
        <ul>
          <li><a href="http://www.awprofessional.com/bookstore/product.asp?isbn=0201379260&amp;rl=1" target="_blank">C++ Standard Library, The: A Tutorial and Reference</a> by Nicolai M. Josuttis.</li>
          <li><a href="http://www.awprofessional.com/bookstore/product.asp?isbn=0201749629&amp;rl=1" target="_blank">Effective STL</a> by Scott Meyers. </li>
          <li>SGI&rsquo;s <a href="http://www.sgi.com/tech/stl/" target="_blank">Standard Template Library Programmer's Guide</a>.</li>
          </ul>
      </li>
      <li>If you feel the need for a humor break while studying C++, the <a href="http://yosefk.com/c++fqa/" target="_blank">C++ FQA</a> may be just what you need.</li>
      </ul>
  </li>
  <li><em>Miscellaneous
    </em>
    <ul>
      <li>If you&rsquo;re interested in designing user interfaces that work and are not <a href="http://annoyances.oreilly.com/" target="_blank">annoying</a>, I highly recommend that you read <a href="http://www.cooper.com/#about:books" target="_blank">About Face</a>, by Alan Cooper</li>
      <li>The <a href="http://www.pcc.edu/library" target="_blank">PCC Library</a> is a great place to look for reference  		materials and more.</li>
      <li>Sylvania&rsquo;s <a href="http://spot.pcc.edu/computers/index.html" target="_blank">Computer Technologies Department</a> offers tutoring, advising, and more.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  </ul>
</div>
